description: Confined within the walls of the Warsaw Ghetto, Dr. Janusz Korczak struggles to protect the children at his orphanage from the horrors of the Second World War. There is not enough food or pairs of eyes to keep watch over them. Between a troublemaking thief, an abandoned girl, a malnourished boy, and a violin prodigy, Janusz has his hands full, but together they fight for beauty and hope in a world crumbling around them. Based on the WWII advocacy work of Dr. Janusz Korczak, The Children's Republic is a reminder of the hope that can still be found in a world devoid of freedom and the necessities of life. Alon Nashman (Shakespeare BASH'd's Merchant of Venice) joins Sarah Orenstein (Stratford's Salesman in China) and four talented students from TanenbaumCHAT in this production directed by the acclaimed Richard Rose.

title: Estelle Singerman: Summer Night, With Unicorn
description: Written by David Rush Directed by David Ferry In the tradition of old Hasidic folktales and awash in magical realism and comic elements, "Estelle Singerman" recounts the relationship between an eccentric, isolated older woman and an equally alone, emotionally disenfranchised middle-aged man named Warren. Foreseeing her imminent death, Estelle searches for someone to say Kaddish for her and decides that Warren is the one. They form an odd duo on an overnight journey through a Chagal-like surreal Chicago where they meet the angel of death in the form of a unicorn and a talking giraffe. By the time the sun comes up, both Estelle and Warren have found faith and peace. WINNER OF THE JEWISH PLAYS PROJECT

Whether you're celebrating with friends or looking for a unique way to spice up your weekend, Forbidden Nights promises an unforgettable evening. Foreseeing her imminent death, Estelle searches for someone to say Kaddish for her and decides that Warren is the one. They form an odd duo on an overnight journey through a Chagal-like surreal Chicago where they meet the angel of death in the form of a unicorn and a talking giraffe. title: 65 Steps Forward
description: 65 Years, 100+ Dancers, One Unforgettable Night! Join the Kodály Ensemble for 65 Steps Forward, a breathtaking celebration of Hungarian folk dance, featuring live music by Gyanta Band. Dancers from seven groups - children, teens, adults, and alumni returning just for this night - come together to honour our past, celebrate our present, and set the stage for the future. From heart-pounding rhythms to intricate partner movements and the unmatched strength of our women, this is folk dance at its most powerful. Experience the rhythm, passion, and tradition like never before! 65 steps forward - it's a celebration of culture, community, and legacy. Founded in 1960 by George Zadubán as a men's choir, they later added a women's choir and folk dance group. From folklore ballet in the 60s & 70s, to ushering in the táncház movement in the 80s/90s to the global village of the 2000s, the Kodaly Ensemble has always been on the forefront of Hungarian Folk Dance.
